 the right to be treated with dignity, that is, with proper respect. At the heart of the argument stands the giant figure of Immanuel Kant. Challenging current orthodoxy, Rosen’s interpretation presents Kant as a philosopher whose ethical thought is governed, above all, by the requirement of showing respect toward a kernel of value that each of us carries, indestructibly, within ourselves. Finally, Rosen asks (and answers) a surprisingly puzzling question: why do we still have a duty to treat the dead with dignity if they will not benefit from our respect?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Mrz 2021) 0aDignity. 0aRespect for persons. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2012z9783110288995oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE PHILOSOPHY  2012z978311029405708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET PHILOSOPHIE  2012z9783110294040oZDB-23-DPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067406551240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674065512423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674065512.jpg  a978-3-11-029405-7  E-BOOK PACKAGE PHILOSOPHY  2012b2012  a978-3-11-044220-5  HUP eBook Package Backlist 2005-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2012  aZDB-23-DPHb2012